    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Attractive, sprawling, rounded shrub growing up to about 1m high. Leaves thick, fleshy and finger-like, pointed at tips and tapering to the base and covered with white hair or grey felt. Abundant, large, bright-yellow flowers present from about July-October. Flowers solitary and borne on leafless stalks with two visible collars of bracts below the flower head.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9475",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Typically reaches a height of about 50 cm, and forms patches at least 1m across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9476",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to Southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to about Wilderness on South Coast.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9477",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common on coastal dunes where can extends almost down to high water mark. The dense covering of white hairs on the leaves reflect light and reduce transpiration. Flowers face to the north and thus heat up rapidly during the day, thus increasing their attractiveness to pollinating bees, flies and beetles.</p><p>The plant is spectacular when in flower and is popular in coastal gardens.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9478",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9479",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers July to October. The hard, flat, saucer-like seeds are covered in spines and this is though to facilitate dispersal by soft-footed mammals.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9480",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The closely-related <i>D. spinosa</i> has wider oval leaves that lack hairs and forms taller, woody shrubs that occurs further inland.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9481",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
